The given problem is a classic example of a clock with a malfunctioning hand speed. However, the question appears to be a trick question. 

When the hands of a clock move at different speeds, the time is the same, but the incorrect clock will display a different time. In a standard clock, the hour hand moves 1/12th of a circle every hour, while the minute hand moves 1/24th of a circle every hour. Therefore, the minute hand moves faster than the hour hand.

In the incorrect scenario described, the hour hand moves at the speed of the minute hand, and the minute hand moves at the speed of the hour hand. This means that each hand completes a full circle every hour. Hence, the hands of the incorrect clock will show the correct time at the same rate as a standard clock.

Therefore, the clock will show the correct time every hour.

Final Answer: $\boxed{1}$
